  "summary": "Generates professional legal billing summaries that consolidate billable hours, expenses, and activities into client-friendly narratives. It organizes data by categories like research, drafting, and communications, providing quantitative breakdowns and qualitative context on work performed and value delivered. Use this skill for law firms and legal departments to ensure transparency in billing for corporate governance matters.",
  "content": "# Legal Billing Summary Generation\n\nYou are tasked with creating a comprehensive legal billing summary that provides clients with a clear, transparent breakdown of billable hours, expenses, and legal activities. This document serves as a critical communication tool between legal service providers and clients, ensuring full transparency in legal costs while demonstrating the value delivered.\n\n## Objective and Scope\n\nGenerate a professional billing summary that consolidates all billable time entries, expenses, and legal activities for a specified billing period. The summary should transform raw time and expense data into a client-friendly narrative that explains what work was performed, why it was necessary, and how it relates to the client's legal matter. This document must balance detailed accounting with readability, allowing both legal and non-legal stakeholders to understand the services rendered and associated costs.\n\n## Required Analysis and Content\n\nBegin by thoroughly reviewing all time entries, expense records, and matter-related documentation for the billing period. Search through uploaded billing records, timesheets, expense reports, and case files to extract complete information about billable activities. Identify patterns in the work performed, major milestones achieved, and how activities align with the overall case strategy or legal objectives.\n\nThe summary should organize billable activities into logical categories such as legal research, document review and drafting, client communications, court appearances, depositions, negotiations, and case strategy. For each category, provide both quantitative data (hours spent, rates applied, total costs) and qualitative context explaining the purpose and outcome of the work. When significant expenses appear, such as expert witness fees, filing costs, travel expenses, or third-party services, include clear explanations of their necessity and relationship to the matter.\n\n## Structure and Format Requirements\n\nPresent the billing summary in a professional format that begins with an executive overview highlighting the total fees, total expenses, and grand total for the billing period. Include the matter name, client name, billing period dates, and responsible attorneys or legal professionals. The executive overview should provide a high-level narrative of the major activities and accomplishments during the period, giving context before diving into detailed breakdowns.\n\nFollowing the overview, organize detailed billing information by attorney or timekeeper, showing individual rates, hours worked, and subtotals. Within each timekeeper's section, group activities by task category or chronologically by significant case events. Each time entry description should be clear and specific enough that a client understands what was done without requiring legal expertise to interpret. Avoid excessive legal jargon or vague descriptions like \"legal research\" without context about the specific issue researched.\n\nCreate a separate expenses section that itemizes all costs with dates, descriptions, and amounts. For recurring or significant expense categories, consider providing subtotals. If the matter involves multiple phases or distinct work streams, consider organizing the summary to reflect these divisions, allowing clients to see how resources were allocated across different aspects of their legal needs.\n\n## Legal and Ethical Considerations\n\nEnsure all billing descriptions maintain attorney-client privilege and do not inadvertently disclose confidential information or work product in a manner that could be discoverable or harmful if the summary were disclosed. Descriptions should be sufficiently detailed for transparency but appropriately general to protect privileged communications and strategic thinking.\n\nVerify that all time entries comply with applicable billing guidelines, including any client-specific billing protocols, rate agreements, or expense policies established in the engagement letter. Flag any entries that may require special explanation, such as block billing that might need to be broken down, or any write-downs or adjustments applied to the raw time entries. If the client has specific billing requirements or restrictions (such as caps on certain activities, prohibited expense types, or required task codes), ensure the summary demonstrates compliance.\n\nBe mindful of ethical billing practices, ensuring that time entries reflect actual work performed, avoid duplication where multiple attorneys worked on the same task, and properly allocate time for administrative versus substantive legal work. If any time has been written off or discounted, consider whether to show this in the summary as a demonstration of value and cost management.\n\n## Context and Best Practices\n\nLegal billing summaries are typically generated monthly or at significant case milestones, though billing frequency may vary based on client agreements or matter type. These summaries serve multiple purposes beyond simple invoicing: they provide clients with regular updates on case progress, demonstrate the value of legal services, support budget management and forecasting, and create a detailed record of work performed that may be relevant for fee disputes, audits, or insurance claims.\n\nWhen preparing summaries for sophisticated clients such as corporate legal departments, expect higher scrutiny and more detailed questions about billing practices. These clients often have established metrics for evaluating legal spend and may compare your billing patterns against industry benchmarks. For individual clients or smaller businesses, the summary may need more explanatory context about legal processes and why certain activities were necessary.\n\nConsider including forward-looking information where appropriate, such as anticipated activities for the next billing period, upcoming deadlines or milestones, and estimated costs for planned work. This helps clients budget and understand the trajectory of their matter. If the matter is approaching significant cost thresholds or budget limits established in the engagement letter, proactively address this in the summary with recommendations for managing costs or adjusting scope.\n\nThe tone should be professional yet accessible, demonstrating both competence and client service orientation. The summary is an opportunity to reinforce the value proposition of your legal services, showing not just what was done but how it advances the client's interests and objectives. Where significant accomplishments occurred during the billing period\u2014such as favorable rulings, successful negotiations, or completion of major deliverables\u2014highlight these achievements to contextualize the investment of time and resources.",
